West Virginia has been declared freeof tuberculosis and brucellosis from its cattle population, theU.S. Agriculture Department said.    It said a state is recognized as tuberculosis-free if nocase of the disease is diagnosed for at least five years and ifthe state complies with the uniform methods and rules of thestate-federal cooperative eradication program.    To achieve brucellosis-free status, a state's cattlepopulation must remain uninfected for the previous 12 months.    There are 33 states, plus the U.S. Virgin Islands,classified as free of bovine tuberculosis and 24 states, plusPuerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands, which have eradicatedbrucellosis. Only 20 states and the U.S. Virgin islands haveeradicated both diseases, it noted. Reuter&#3;